The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Dunlop to clear retirement dues
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Dunlop to clear retirement dues
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Calcutta, March 11: The 436 workers of Dunlop who had taken voluntary retirement four years ago will finally get their dues by December. About 1,500 workers had taken voluntary retirement in 2006, of which these 436 were yet to receive their dues.        
	State labour minister Anadi Sahoo today held a meeting at Writers Buildings with Pawan Ruia, chairman of Dunlop India Limited, and discussed the payment of the early retirement scheme benefits for the Sahagunj workers who had opted for them in 2006 but hadnt been paid till now. Dunlop has two facilities  at Sahagunj in Bengal and Ambattur in Tamil Nadu.        
	After the meeting the labour minister said, When the company reopened in 2006, 1,500 employees had opted for the early retirement scheme (ERS). All but 436 of them were paid their dues and benefits available under the scheme. The company chairman said he would try to clear the ERS dues of the remaining 436 employees between April and December this year. At present, the company has 1,007 employees.        
	Ruia today said that currently the company was producing 500-600 tyres every day. This amounts to about 25 tonnes. We want to increase this to 30 tonnes.        
	Labour commissioner Satyabrata Chakraborty said that todays meeting was more in the nature of a review.         
	Ruia took over the troubled tyre company in end 2005 from Dubai-based Jumbo group owned by the Chhabria family.                                                                                                                                       
